## **Describe the permission strings:**

Previously, by saying see permissions by using the command ***‘ls \-l’*** we see some arranged string together with dash separators on the left side.   
For instance:  
Permission strings are designated up by 3 different members that include: “user”, “group”, and  “other”. In addition there are 3 major features or actions one as a member can do with the file which are read **(r),** write **(w),** execute **(x)**. The 10 string character establishes those permissions by granting them according to what the owner of the file wants them to do. Let’s categorize it:

1) **1st Character:** The first character is either a `d` or a dash (`-`). If it’s a `d`, that means it’s a folder. If it’s just a dash, then it’s a normal file.  
2) **2nd-4th characters**: These characters indicate the read (r), write (w), and execute (x) permissions for the user. When one of these characters is a hyphen (\-) instead, it indicates that this permission is not granted to the user.  
3) **5th-7th characters:** These characters indicate the read (r), write (w), and execute (x) permissions for the group. When one of these characters is a hyphen (\-) instead, it indicates that this permission is not granted for the group.  
4) **8th-10th characters:** These characters indicate the read (r), write (w), and execute (x) permissions for other. This owner type consists of all other users on the system apart from the user and the group. When one of these characters is a hyphen (\-) instead, that indicates that this permission is not granted for other.

## **Change file permissions:**

In some cases the owner of the file wants the “other” members to not have any sort of editable permission, so in this case we want to change the permission on the “other” member subset to no have anymore the “write”action on file **‘project\_k.txt’** so on line 9 as you can see above we use the command ***‘chmod’*** to establish that. After, we use the **‘o-w’** to disallowed member for writing followed by the file name.  
We do this again later on, on the file named **‘project\_m.txt’** but now to not let ‘group’ access to reading option by using again the  ***‘chmod’*** command.

## **Change file permissions on a hidden file:**

To see any hidden file within a folder we use the command ***‘ls \-la’*** and hidden files usually starts by a period at the beginning of its name in this case the file **“.project\_x.txt”** is a hidden file shown on line 5\. We want to change its permissions so that the ‘user’ and ‘group’ only have read mode available granted anything else should be dashed. So, we use the command ***‘chmod’*** followed by the little piece of code that is ***‘u-w,g-w,g+r’*** and the followed by the file name and the result is on line 27 of the image above.
